			<div class="post-2461 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-jp-morgan tag-jp-morgan">

				<div class="entry">

					<h2><a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/2012/05/31/jpm-max-pain-at-6-month-highs-zerohedge/">JPM Max Pain At 6 Month Highs&nbsp;[Zerohedge]</a></h2>

					<div class="post-info">
						<p>
							<span class="time">May 31, 2012</span>
															<span class="author">by <a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/author/mktgeistmike/" title="Posts by mktgeistmike" rel="author">mktgeistmike</a></span>
																						<span class="post-comments"><a href="http://blog.mktgeist.com/2012/05/31/jpm-max-pain-at-6-month-highs-zerohedge/#respond" title="Comment on JPM Max Pain At 6 Month Highs&nbsp;[Zerohedge]">Leave a comment</a></span>
																				</p>
					</div>

					<p>While we can argue over which exact position Iksil and his crew had on, the widening in IG9 10Y spreads post-Dimon signals an unwind of epic proportions continues. It seems the mainstream media has grown tired of discussing skews, basis, curves, tranches, and tail-risk but for those who care about the reality that JPMorgan faces &#8211; we note that the <strong>credit index most closely tied to the CIO&#8217;s office debacle continues to push wider</strong>.</p>
<p><img src="http://www.zerohedge.com/sites/default/files/images/user3303/imageroot/2012/05-2/20120530_IG910y_0.png" alt="" width="500" height="364" /></p>
